https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-battery-cells-cost-per-kwh-revealed-gm-competitors-cairn-report/ Offers an interesting look at current industry costs using 2020 data. "According to Cairn’s research, Tesla pays an average of $142 per kWh for cells purchased from its three previously mentioned suppliers. Meanwhile, companies like GM are paying $169 per kWh, while the industry average runs around $186, according to the firm’s report. Furthermore, Tesla’s packs cost $187 per kWh on average, with GM’s costing $207 per kWh and the industry average being $246 per kWh."

The industry-wide average cost of Li-ion batteries decreased by about 15% in 2020. The expectation is that by 2023 the price will be $101 per kWh. Given that with technology like this is becomes increasingly difficult to cut costs over time, I predict that the most likely scenario is the batteries will cost just over $100 by the end of 2022.
This is because there has been a decrease in the price of a Li-ion battery.

I just learned today that more than half of the total cost of a Li-ion battery is caused by the material for anode and cathode. So a lot depends on the market conditions and long-term contracts for these materials (probably precious/rare metals, among others) and mass production by just a handful of companies (Samsung, Panasonic, LG,...), and on the other hand R&D in material science to probably find structures and molecules that behave like the classical electrode material but are much cheaper, and possibly bring along some functional improvement or with regards to charge duration, total capacity, number of life cycles, safety, easier processable. Noting the plans and targets of Tesla as announced on their battery day 2020 have become more cautious when it comes to ambitions on the field of time frame and price, then Tesla Inc. which for the time being have a partnership with contractors but are planning a battery manufacturing of their own could achieve a price of maybe 135 USD/kWh and reduce the price to 95USD/kWh in 2022 - the potential of cost cuts in Li-ion technology is not unlimited. As the question asks for "the industry-wide average cost of battery packs", my forecast takes account of proximity to the boundary of 100USD between the bins 2 and 3 on the one hand, and on the other hand of the uncertainty about the question, whether Tesla will be successful in the attempt to transform itself from a "battery pack consuming" car manufacturer into a self-serving battery pack producer, and whether its cost then lie under, at or above industry-wide average prices. One thing is clear, as the importance of EVs for the (European and worldwide) car manufacturers has increased dramatically and seem to determine their fate over the next decade, battery pack production has more than ever turned into a cut-throat competition, which will make the industry-wide average price(s) fall and adapt rather fast than slowly, as production capacity will spike in 2021.

Battery prices are falling but reports indicate lithium ion technology may not have a lot of room to drop in price. Even if they continue to drop at 15% a year that puts prices closer to $97. But it sounds to me like that is unlikely. The linked estimate (found from @benjuliano1 on another question) puts it at $94 in 2024, and that's at 2018 dollars. Seems most likely it doesn't drop below $100 in 2022.

Extrapolating the (fairly stable over longer time intervals) trend of 16% decline per year, starting at 161$ in 2019, we get a projected price of 95$. The category cutoffs are at (geometric) average yearly declines of 4.5%, 9.3%, 14.7% and 20.8%. Forecast before seeing crowd: 15|53|20|10|2 Crowd: 5|29|51|15|0 Adjusted forecast: 12|50|26|10|2

If market share in EVs rises as expected, lithium will become scarce, and to my knowledge there's no way hedging the price except physical hedge. Cost-efficient production of lithium depends on very few deposit countries, with the risk of nationalization of common stock companies and administered prices pending. After a trough in lithium price this year, price could see a transient increase similar to rare earths.
